profile_positions.description:
Leading the work on the Data & Evidence output of the regional office with a focus on providing technical support to regional office sectors and UNICEF South Asia country offices in the fields of data, research, statistics and monitoring. Coordinating Multiple Indicator Cluster Survey (MICS) across South Asia.

Core duties:

•	Technical support to UNICEF Country Offices and their partners for planning, designing and 
        implementing South Asia Strategy on Data for Children;
•	Coordinate the Multiple Indicator Cluster Survey, UNICEF’s flagship household survey programme, and other surveys in South Asia;
•	Strengthen the data mining, analytical, research and statistical capacity of UNICEF staff, national statistical offices and officials;
•	Communicate and showcase of relevant trends and developments in data for children to UNICEF management, statistical offices and other (governmental) stakeholders;
•	Contribute to global learning and methodological development of tools for data on children related to the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs);
•	Lead the Knowledge Management in the regional office in support of KM work in the sections and country offices;
•	Contribute to planning & monitoring at the RO and COs as part of the Programme and Planning 
        team, including co-authoring to the ROMP and quality assuring CPDs, theories of change and 
        monitoring frameworks in South Asia;
•	Contribute to the on-going improvement of the global UNICEF data portal (data.unicef.org).

Heading AHF’s Data and Analytics department which covers all of AHF’s prevention and treatment activities in the global program, which currently includes 300+ facilities in 30 countries in Asia, Africa, Europe and Latin America. 

Core Duties: 

• Responsible for all activities carried out in AHFs global data department including all prevention and care & treatment activities;
• Provide individual contributions as well as leadership to bureau and country-level data and quality staff in 30 countries; 
• Provide guidance and strengthen the capacity staff to more effectively collect, manage and analyse data on the impacts of their programs and interventions;
• Design, implement and evaluate national and regional M&E plans;
• Provide short-term technical consultations and support in HIV technical areas and institutional capacity building to AHF country and bureau data and quality teams;
• Support and drive the renewed focus on quality of care through development of safe, welcoming, and supportive medical and social service environments that foster improvement in linkage, engagement and retention in HIV prevention and care services among our clients worldwide, including regular HIV testing and antiretroviral treatment for HIV;
• Prepare and present quarterly quality reports to the Board of Directors and members of senior management;
• Co-responsible for the creation of AHF’s global research department for high quality (operations) research aimed at quality of care improvements and enhancement of testing, linkage and treatment outcomes;
• Work closely with the Finance Department in terms of modelling and predicting census developments and performance;
• Document and disseminate successful innovative approaches and sustainable models, evidence-based best practices and lessons learned, and new approaches, tools and methodologies in HIV programming, through workshops, working papers, publications and attendance of (international) conferences.

Data analyst, data manager and coach within AHF’s Global Program, which covers more than 170 clinics in over 22 countries in Asia, Africa, Europe and Latin America. 

Core Duties: 

•	Provide long-term, in-country support for coordination and scale-up of data management systems in 20 countries; 
•	Provide short-term technical consultations and support in HIV technical areas and institutional capacity building to AHF country and bureau data and M&E teams;
•	Increase technical and research capacity of country and site-level decision-makers and personnel to design and implement effective, evidence-based HIV interventions;
•	Strengthen the capacity of site and country-level staff to more effectively manage and analyse data about the impacts of their HIV and AIDS interventions;
•	Conduct and/or oversee implementation of HIV and AIDS program-related data collection, analysis and reporting activities; 
•	Document and disseminate successful innovative approaches and sustainable models, evidence-based best practices and lessons learned, and new approaches, tools and methodologies in HIV and AIDS programming and capacity building, through workshops, working papers and (international) conferences.
•	Designing, monitoring and researching (especially linkage, retention, client flows and care outcomes) at AHF’s Test & Treat projects in Umlazi, South Africa and Masaka in Uganda
•	Design, implement and evaluate national and regional M&E plans
